<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Helvetica, sans-serif">
The way I've seen it explained is that all items with the exception of artifacts will decay.  Repairing will return them to their normal strngth, but their durability will be decreased.  The end result being that the more times an item has been reapired, the quicker it will decay.<P>This has been done intentionally, as part of the anti-twinking mechanics.  You can give a low-level player good items, but they will decay faster, and eventualy become relatively useless.  I think this is a great idea, and will make many of the more "ordinary" items much more desireable. <P>An added effect of this will be that it should to some extent limit the horrendous inflation that has shown itself in the player driven economies on other games&lt;cough&gt;druid farmers&lt;cough&gt;.<P>It very much like this idea, and hope that they do not implement a way for items not to decay.  I don't think they will though, since they have explained in depth their reasons for doing this.<P>I remember seeing somewhere, in one of the FAQ's I believe, that items will have a durability score.  Each durability point would be equivalent to 10 hours of rigorous use.  when an item is repaired it would lose one durability.<P>I can't say for certain on this, as I am speaking from memory, but I think that's the basic idea.  And of course, like everything else, it is subject to change before realease.<P>Hope this helps clear up your questions a little.<P>--------------------<P>"When in panic, when in doubt.  Run in circles, sceam and shout."<P>Explorer 66% | Killer 53% | Achiever 46% | Socializer 33%<P>NF idealist(figures)
</FONT>
